neighborhood_overview: The Upper West Side—bracketed by Central Park and Riverside Park, and distinguished by regal, two-towered apartment buildings along Central Park West—is a place where you can frequently see families pushing strollers, walking dogs and, on weekends, settling in for brunch at mainstays like Sarabeth's.  Of course, it's not all residential. There's culture, in the form of the American Museum of Natural History, the Beacon Theatre and Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts. And plenty of shopping, eating and nightlife as well.  There's a long menu of area places to sit down for a dinner. Among them: Asian-fusion dim sum favorite RedFarm; new-kid-on-the-block Mediterranean eatery Tessa, whose desserts like dulce de leche pot de creme and lemon-thyme and ginger panna cotta have generated as much buzz as the main courses; The Leopard at des Artistes, which picks up where the beloved Café des Artistes left off (and preserves the Howard Chandler Christy paintings from its predecessor); and Bar

neighborhood_overview: South Harlem is one of the most charming neighborhoods in Manhattan, and particularly the area I'm in on Frederick Douglass Blvd. There are a ton of locally owned and run restaurants, bars, and coffee shops all within 5-10 blocks of my apartment. But my favorite part is the parks: Morningside Park is a mere 2 blocks west, and Central Park is 7 blocks south.
notes: As I mentioned in the listing, I have two cats and a dog. The two cats are named Jeremiah (grey one in the bedroom photo) and Naomi (fluffy one in the kitchen photo.) They are both not at all aggressive and Jeremiah acts more like a puppy than a cat, so I hope you like snuggles! Moses, my dog, travels with me or stays with a friend when I'm gone, but the cats get mad if I try to bring them anywhere besides the apartment, so they will be there while you stay. As shared in the listing description, my apartment is listed at about 15% below the market rate for comparable apartments as a result, but please let me know when you book if you would rather a pet-sitter comes 1-2x/day to feed them and clean the litterbox during your stay instead.
transit: The B/C train is conveniently located just a block away, which can get you downtown or further uptown, and there are plenty of buses that can take you crosstown if you need. There are also plenty of cabs in the area and usually plenty of Ubers (or Uber alternatives) around as well.
access: For longer stays, I will clear a drawer for you to use in the dresser, but otherwise please stay out of the bedroom closet, dresser, and vanity. Of course you are welcome to use the vanity to get ready - the lighting is amazing for make-up! I work in beauty so it's one of my favorite spaces in the apartment :)
interaction: I may be traveling internationally during your stay, but I have lots of close friends (and fellow AirBnBers) in the neighborhood who can help with any immediate needs. I also can always be reached on my cell phone regardless of where I am, and I will share that number with you upon confirming your reservation.
house_rules: NOTE: I have a dog and two cats. The dog travels with me but sadly the cats cannot. I am fastidiously clean and have a Roomba that vacuums 1-2x a day, every day, but pets are pets so there may be some fur and dander in the apartment. If you don't like or are allergic to animals, this may not be the best fit for you.  They are both very sweet and easy! If you prefer to have someone come in and take care of them during your stay, I can arrange that as well. I will happily leave you some basics in the fridge and of course all necessities are included (eg: towels, sheets, pillows,) but I do ask that you not partake from the bar. You are more than welcome welcome to bring your own alcohol into the house but please don't drink mine ;)

host_about:
I am a young professional working in digital marketing in New York City. I love traveling (obviously, or I wouldn't be here!)  Some of my favorite places I've been are Paris, Hong Kong, and Sydney.

In my spare time, I enjoy walking in Central Park with my dog,  Moses (who unfortunately does not travel with me) as well as exploring my own city of New York where there's always a new restaurant to discover!

I sometimes travel alone when extending business trips or with a few friends. I've been using AirBnB for a number of years and have had some lovely experiences that I hope to continue.

neighborhood_overview: Yorkville is the Upper East Side neighborhood you will b staying in. It's awesome yes, but more for grown-ups. If you want a clubbing weekend, head farther south to Midtown or Specifically Hells Kitchen and the Meatpacking Districts. The Yorkville neighborhood is older but true NY and sparse on tourists. It's also home to Gracie Mansion, several celebrities, and many high net worth individuals. Every Avenue offers you something new - from the East River Park to Central Park, there are many amazing restaurants, shops and museums in between. And as many dogs as people! neighborhood_overview: The highly desired neighborhood is quite lively after the sun goes down. The East Village has been heavily built up over the last 5-10 years and located on the East side of Manhattan from 14th St down to Houston (same as street zero) which borders the LES (Lower East Side). Tompkins Square Park is a block away, which has basketball courts, dog run and plenty of benches and grassy areas to relax. You can walk to Indian, Russian, Italian, Mexican, Japanese, Chinese, Thai, Vegetarian and American restaurants within a 5 block radius. If you're too tired and beat up from touring NYC and don't feel like going anywhere, you can simply order in and have anything delivered to the room (usually until 11 pm or midnight). And these little privately owned restaurants are MUCH better than midtown/tourist-trap food chain places. There are at least three 24/hr places to eat within 2 blocks.  There are about 50 restaurant/bars/cafe's within a 3 block radius and probably 500 within a 10 block radius.
notes: Please understand this is NOT a hotel! Daily maid services are not included. This is for use of a furnished apartment (bungalow) rental and loud noise will not be tolerated as there are full time tenants/neighbors that work normal business hours and my neighbors peace cannot and will not be disrupted. If you're a group of drinkers/clubbers who will be out late and loud at night, please do NOT inquire.
transit: Subway (L, F, V) are about a 10 minute walk, or you can catch a bus on the closest corner and a 10 minute ride to Union Square where you can take any subway line to get anywhere in NYC.. Taxis everywhere, usually takes a minute or two standing in front of building. I highly recommend walking. After living here my entire life, I've found it pretty much takes 20-40 minutes to get anywhere in Manhattan, FROM anywhere in Manhattan. Walking is free, by far the safest way to travel and you get to see cool stuff along the way and don't have to wait for anything.

A mix of all different types of folks and endless numbers of interesting boutiques, gourmet food/drinks, hairdressers and everything between. LES has some of the best food/drink/treats available all within walking distance from my apartment. (Schiller's Liquor Bar, Doughnut Plant, Clinton Street Baking Company, WD-50 Restaurant, Il Laboratorio del Gelato, Katz's Deli...). Also walking distance to SoHo, Chinatown, Little Italy. Short walk to Delancey/Essex Subway station with easy travel anywhere in the city.

neighborhood_overview: Our block, between First and Second Avenues is completely residential. In most of Manhattan, and especially in this neighborhood, the nearer one stays to an avenue or on an avenue (rather than on a street), and the nearer one stays to transportation centers (here Lexington and 116th and 125th Streets) the greater the noise level and the denser the traffic and crowds. I urge you to read the reviews from prior guests to gain their appreciation of the neighborhood. The neighborhood is quite safe at all hours. I do suggest that guests might feel more comfortable if they use a taxi when returning after about 11:00 pm. People are very friendly and will go out of their way to be helpful.
notes: PRICING--IMPORTANT: The price you will be quoted by AirBnb already includes a discount for stays of 7 nights or longer. Also, I have been asked in the last several inquiries (in early June 2016) to provide the total cost for a stay. I AM UNABLE TO DO THAT, BECAUSE: (1) if you are inquiring from within the United States, your cost will be shown in US. However, that cost includes a commission that you pay to AirBnb. I do not know what the commission rate is and I have no control over the amount of that commission. (2) If you inquire from outside the US, I believe your total cost is shown in your country's currency. I have no idea what exchange rate AirBnb applies and no control over that exchange rate. Also, as said above, I have no control over the rate or amount of commission AirBnb charges you, as a guest. On my end of the transaction, I see only the gross amount in US that I will receive based on my daily or weekly rates; AirBnb also deducts a commission from that payment to me bef
transit: I will provide a neighborhood map on arrival that locates bus and subway stops as well as shopping highlights. The walk to the nearest subway stop is about 8 minutes. Buses are available within a block and half. Please (SENSITIVE CONTENTS HIDDEN) NYC or Manhattan transportation so you have an idea of the subway network. The nearest line is Lexington Ave (Green line on the maps) which runs the entire length of Manhattan and is one of the most convenient methods of transport you will find in Manhattan. I have many maps and sight-seeing brochures to aid you in coordinating your stay.
access: We are a semi-retired professional couple who delight in meeting new people. We converted this four story brownstone in 1985-87 and have been living here since.  We do have an arrival (3:00 pm and later) and departure (11:00 am) schedule which we appreciate your meeting if possible. However, we are quite flexible. If no guests arrive the next day, you are welcome to stay later; if no guests have departed the previous day, you are welcome to arrive earlier. If your arrival will be late in the day (i.e. evening or night) please let me know so we can best coordinate a smooth introduction.   Please note that we insist on no smoking or drugs or partying in and about the house and the apartment and no guests of guests! We are a quiet couple who prefer classical music and gentle R&R to R&B and certainly to rap--which will be freely available as you wander nearby streets. Please, no pets.
interaction: The degree of interaction is entirely up to you.  We are happy to provide a light breakfast or even simple meals to enjoy in the apartment for the first day or two until you are settled in and acclimated to our local time if you are travelling from outside the US.  We have a small Maltese dog, "Lady Windermere." She appears in one of the photos, though her favorite spot is on my shoulder. As you may know, the breed is hypoallergenic and does not shed. She is sweet and lively and may bark until she comes to know you. By the time you leave, you may want to take her with you, but we will not allow that. On the other hand, you need not see her or us for your entire stay if that is your wish. I do communicate with you before your arrival regarding transportation to and from the house. And, I do check in on you during your stay to make sure everything is to your satisfaction. I am always available to answer questions.  Please read the reviews to gain an impression of me and my hosting style.
house_rules: No smoking, drugs or partying in the Apartment. A complete list of Apartment procedures is available on booking.

neighborhood_overview: At its core, the neighborhood has always been a diverse one - mixing an older Irish-American crowd with a growing Latino community. Throw into the mix plenty of Columbia Med School students in scrubs and off-duty cops and that will round out the scene at many a happy hour in the Heights. Stay at the heart of Upper Manhattan area Washington Heights , walking distance to the George Washington bridge, delicious restaurants, happening bars, and more! Kitchen is accessible and there are two large supermarkets just one and two blocks away. Apartment is one block away from subway line A which will connect you to the entire city! Apartment is 15-20 min ride from Times Square and other attractions away. This is a two bedroom apartment. Rooms for guests are air conditioned with full size bed. Complimentary WiFi, iron, hair dryer .  This is a charming building built in 1900. The apartment is on the first floor. If you want to visit NYC and have the New York experience, this is the place to be!
notes: - Actual address will be send to your phone
transit: The "1" train and "A" train is conveniently located a few blocks away. The subway is 2.75 per ride and you can access anywhere in NYC for that price. Only 15-20 minutes away from cloud-punching high-rises, megawatt billboards, honking taxis - Midtown is movie set New York. Stay here and you'll be a few train stops away of Times Square, the Empire State Building and the Rockefeller Center, plus the bright lights of Broadway and shopping icons Bloomingdale's and Saks. The area's concentration of businesses means that whether you're craving a humble hot dog to a Michelin-starred feast, you'll find it here, and for ethnic eats don't miss to Korea town and Murray (aka Curry) Hill. Further south, Chelsea is contemporary art's HQ and home to the High Line, a sublime public park on an elevated railroad with the views to match. neighborhood_overview: Comfortably fitting two on a quiet tree lined street, this home is perfect for those that want to experience Manhattan without being crowded into a tiny crammed hotel room. The apartment is located in one of the most luxurious neighborhoods in the city and is a great place to feel at home while being away from home.  I love everything about my neighborhood. Mostly residential, the street is quiet at night and busy during the day. There are many people out walking the dogs or taking children to the park, and I always feel quite safe.  Within close proximity are many restaurants and bars, I always find a new one to try when walking around, so I am never bored! I am close to Central Park when I want to escape the 'hustle and bustle' of the city. There is plenty of shopping in the area with new stores coming in all of the time. It is easy to get almost anywhere in the city via bus transportation, subway, or simply walking.  There are multiple hospitals in the area and many doctors offices.
notes: SAFETY!: I live in a building with double door entry for extra security. I cannot even buzz a guest in without the guest buzzing my apartment number first, for both doors. I feel very safe with that entry system, as uninvited guests will find it very difficult to enter. There is also a channel on my television that will allow me to view the street and lobby area live. Parking:  Street parking is available (though limited). Circling the nearby blocks for a few minutes can increase your likelihood of finding a decent parking spot. If you are parking on the street, please make sure to double and triple check the signage. A vehicle parked incorrectly will no doubt receive a parking ticket within even a few minutes. My area has both metered and non-metered parking. There are also street cleaning hours, where no parking is allowed during certain periods on certain days. As I live near a post office, there are also Government Vehicles Only spots. There are parking garages available in my area
transit: Public Transportation:  Public Transportation is extremely convenient. The 6 train is conveniently located approximately a five minute walk away. The 6 train connects to E 59th Street, Grand Central Station, Union Square, The East Village, and many other convenient locations. The 6 train also connects to every other train line. Local busses are also available within one block. Taxis pass very often and can be hailed by raising your arm to signal the driver. I suggest walking to either corner for taxis as they are more frequent on the busier streets. Uber is available in the city, however Lyft can be SIGNIFICANTLY cheaper. There is also Gett, which offers 10 flat rates for anywhere in Manhattan for up to 4 passengers, and under 30 minute trips (which most will be from my area). I usually check each of the apps for each trip I take to price-check which is cheapest and fastest.  Parking:  Street parking is available (though limited). interaction: Any time the guests require assistance, I can be reached by phone. Any time guests require my presence, I can usually be reached within four hours.

neighborhood_overview: Museum Mile! The Met, Guggenheim, Cooper Hewitt, and many other world renowned museums within walking distance. Close to Central Park. This apartment is my home; it is available when I am traveling for work. As is common and constants in NYC, there is construction happening around the apartment.
transit: Across the street from Q train entrances- less than a minute walk! 6 minute walk from local subway train, 10 minutes from express subway stop. access: Key pick-up: I use keycafe to ensure your ability to access the keys. Keys are available for pick up from 8 am to 6 pm at a nearby location 2 blocks away. I can make keys available 24/7 upon your request, but the location is less convenient. Check in and check out times: often, I can accommodate earlier check-ins and later check-outs. If this is something that interests you, please include this in your inquiry and I will do my best to work with you. Guests may open and use the contents of dish cabinet, sink cabinet, silverware drawer, and bedside table. However, all other drawers, cabinets, and closets in the space should not be opened, as this is my home.
interaction: I will be available by text to answer any questions about the space and the neighborhood! If there's anything you need, please text!
house_rules: No parties- no more than 5 individuals in the space at a time. No loud music, and please no yelling or jumping.  No pets. Sorry :( Building rules. No smoking inside the apartment or building. Please no smoking on the fire escape as the smoke wafts into other apartments and disturbs the neighbors.  Wash any used dishes. Do not leave food out.  Please be mindful of noise level. Please be courteous to neighbors.  Close windows, turn off lights, and shut off air conditioner whenever leaving the apartment. Use any candles responsibly - always ensure an adult is present when they are lit and extinguish them before leaving.  Hang any wet or damp towels in the bathroom.  At the end of the stay, please hang keys on key hook near intercom.  Please note that this is my home, and as such, please do not open closets or any drawers, other than those noted above.

neighborhood_overview: The Upper West Side—bracketed by Central Park and Riverside Park, and distinguished by regal, two-towered apartment buildings along Central Park West—is a place where you can frequently see families pushing strollers, walking dogs and, on weekends, settling in for brunch at mainstays like Sarabeth's. neighborhood_overview: We live on the boarder of the Sugar Hill neighborhood home to a great many Jazz legends from the Golden age of jazz. Just around the corner on Broadway is a fantastic Harlem classic called the Harlem Public for amazing draft beers and modern soul-fare, a little further down from that is the chipped cup the best coffee in Harlem (easy to miss as its in the basement), also if you walk west on 149th past broadway you'll hit riverside park where you can take a fantastic romantic walk or morning run along the water. We're on express trains that take you quickly to the lower parts of the island and to Central Park in no time at all. Super accessible and tons of great eating and delivery options of you just want to cozy up in Harlem, too.
notes: Do not be alarmed if you hear hissing or sounds like someone is banging on a pipe! This is just our old school new york heating system doing its thing! Also, note that we do not have control over the heat as the building is all on the same system it is ALWAYS warm enough, but if you get TOO warm you can just open the door to the balcony as much as you need (I know, seems crazy) or if the temperature outside is above freezing you can turn on the air conditioner - please keep the screen closed to we don't get bugs in the house and please please do not use the air conditioner if the temperature outside is below freezing, ice forms in the air conditioner and it will blow out the motor!
transit: closest subway stations are 145th street (closest entrance on St. Nicholas between 148 and 147 street) for the B/D and A/C or a DIFFERENT 145th St. station on Broadway and 145th for the 1 local train (from which you can transfer to the 2/3 express). Also, a great way to get around in the city is Uber (get the app on your phone) which is even cheaper if you select UberPool
access: You will have access to the whole apartment, the closets and drawers are full though so pleas don't move things around, if you really need a drawer or space in the closet please message us to work out us clearing some space ahead of your arrival.
interaction: you can always send us a message and we'll try and get back to you as soon as possible!
house_rules: We simply ask that our guests be respectful of our house and our neighbors.  For our neighbors- No late night parties, inside-voices on the balcony late at night and in the stairwell of the building at all times (we all live pretty close together in the city!) and please do not throw any trash not even cigarette butts off of the balcony (we have an ash tray for that!). Please no stomping competitions or Tim, our downstairs neighbor, will kill us when we get back!  For our house - Generally just please treat our stuff with care as you would your own. You are welcome to use teas coffees, oil/spices, any perishable fruit or veg we may have left behind for you, and condiments, but please don't eat our other food or drink our booze! Also, if you break something, please let us know immediately so we can tell you how much cash to leave for replacement. On that note, please don't use the crystal glasses because, I promise you, you don't want to have to pay to replace those!

host_about:
We're a Tennessee boy and Seattle gal who traded the rainy days and country hills for city thrills, vowing to learn the constant lessons of an adventurous and passionate life. 

Traveling is, by far, our favorite thing to do. We believe it's essential to a fulfilling life. Mark Twain said it best — “Twenty years from now you will be more disappointed by the things you didn’t do than by the ones you did do. So throw off the bowlines, sail away from the safe harbor. Catch the trade winds in your sails. Explore. Dream. Discover.”

Our list of places we've traveled covers the globe, including Ireland (where Matt's relatives are from), Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Yellowstone National Park, Whistler British Columbia, Hungary, Germany, Kenya, Galapagos Islands, New Zealand, Australia, Thailand, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, Mexico, all of western Europe, Morocco and so many more to come... 

In between trips, Matt works as a creative director at an advertising agency, while Allie runs her own interior design firm (thus our place has a professional designer's personal touch!)

neighborhood_overview: "The East Village is downtown's most livable neighborhood. Blame that on all the well-worn tenements and their (relatively) affordable small studios and "junior" one-bedrooms, some of them rent stabilized. In these apartments dwell old timers, NYU kids, and everyone in between, making for awesome people watching, day or night. A stroll through Tompkins Square Park on any warm weekend pretty much sums it up. Cute pooches and their oh-so-hip owners convene at the dog run while bongo drums echo over near Avenue B. Little kids shriek at the playground while crusty punks and gritty old men occupy the benches on the Southwestern side. Just a typical slice of life in the East Village, and a sweet life it is if you can swing the rent." -- Not For Tourists  (URL HIDDEN)

neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is not only home to me, but all of my favorite places. There are countless boutique shops, top-rated restaurants opening every time you blink (a couple that are Michelin rated), night life and performance venues, as well as art galleries and museums (the new museum is a must) all within a couple blocks. After you've explored the area and the sun is beginning to set, hop on a citi bike, or just walk the Williamsburg bridge, where a whole new world of fun awaits.  Within a five-ten minute walk lies Soho (fashion capital), the East Village (historic landmark full of bars and restaurants), and the West Village (Washington Square Park and NYU).
notes: If you stand at our front door and pick up a rock I guarantee you hit an amazing restaurant, a bar with a unique and cool vibe, or a very unlucky person. We have no fewer than 4 favorite coffee shops and none of them are Starbucks. Every time we try to save money and pledge to make our own food we shatter our resolutions within 48 hours because of how great the restaurants in NYC are (for real tho, we are not kidding). The master bedroom (w/ queen "Heavenly Bed") is tucked away behind custom pocket doors (to accommodate 3-4 guests, an optional queen can be set up in the lounge area on the other side of the loft).

neighborhood_overview: This neighborhood is called Yorkville, a special corner of the Upper East Side which is close to the action, but just far enough to get some peace and quiet when you need it.  Head East for one of the best parks in the city, Carl Schurz where you can enjoy views of the East River, Astoria, the RFK and Queensboro bridges, as well as walk past Gracie Mansion (Mayor's House) and a couple dog runs filled with the neighborhood pets.  Head West and enjoy the many restaurants on 1st, 2nd and 3rd Avenue, stroll through Central Park, and visit the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Guggenheim, or the Neue Gallery (Woman in Gold).  Our favorite spots to eat include Beyoglu (Turkish), Om (Indian), Nick's (Pizza), Poke (BYOB Sushi), Up Thai, Cavatappo (Italian), and the Gilroy (cocktails).  There's also some great local coffee spots (Joe, Petite Shell, Jax).  Or hop on the express train or crosstown bus and explore all that this city has to offer.
notes: HBO, Showtime, Netflix, Apple TV
transit: Our apartment is steps from the express crosstown bus, as well as the 86th street express subway stop (on the 4,5,6 line).  You can walk to the subway or get a free transfer from the bus to the subway (just make sure to swipe before you hop on the bus and keep your receipt).  One swipe gets you anywhere in the city and if you need help, just ask someone...New Yorkers are friendly and always happy to get to show off their knowledge of how to get around NYC.
access: Guests have access to everything except the bedroom closet.  Please note we no longer have the espresso machine.

house_rules: I’m a strong believer in the Golden Rule: do to others as you would have others do to you! Please treat my home as if it were your home. If you have questions about what zero tolerance means please ask. We do not allow parties or portable speakers of any kind in the apartment. The space is large and suitable for certain events; please ask! We do not allow groups whose main constituency is under 25 years of age.  While most check-ins will be done without meeting us, we may request a form of identification upon check-in. Failure to provide such at that time will result in immediate cancellation on your behalf.  Additional procedural information about the apartment is provided upon booking! We'd love to have you!

host_about:
I have been living in New York for at least 10 years now. In 2008, my husband and I left our small one bedroom in the Upper East Side, to buy this beautiful duplex in Harlem, New York. We are extremely happy with our choice, we love the apartment, we have wonderful neighbors and the neighborhood is so interesting and friendly.
My husband is Italian and I am half Italian, half French. I am working as a consultant for international organizations in the field of rural development and the environment. I have to travel a lot for my work, and I spend a few months overseas every year. Francesco, my husband, is director of programming of a cultural center in Staten Island, with the aim to promote Italian culture in the US. He is also traveling quite a lot.
What else... we have 2 kids (they come with me when I travel), and a small dog (who is not aloud to go in the floor where the bedrooms are). He is also traveling with us.. 
Our interests? New York, New York and New York... Reading, theater, music, friends, outdoors and travelling. 
I am also renting my apartment in the Alps, in Piedmont, Italy. Unfortunately, now that I am living in New York, I have no opportunities to spend time there. It is a great place for both summer and winter holidays.

name: Basic Studio in Heart of Chinatown/Lower East Side
summary: If you're reasonable and understand that you get what you pay for, you will love this place. Located in the Chinatown/Lower East Side neighborhood of Lower Manhattan, it's an easy walk to City Hall and the Financial District as well. Comfy bed, fast wifi, good heat, warm bath/shower, cute balcony to hang out, good air mattress available, cool antique sofa. And that's it. Nearby 3 subways Wanna cook? You're a jerk. I have no pots or pans or plates for you. Go out to eat. You're in Chinatown.
space: Simple. It's Chinatown, 5th floor walk up. The place is gonna be kind of dirty. At 100 a night I'm the cheapest in Lower Manhattan by quite a lot, so please keep your expectations low (nearby hotels are 250). Great little balcony, warm heat, comfy, big bed. Place naturally attracts dust. If you come here looking to find tiny things you won't like, you'll find them. So stay home, I don't get mad if you book and then read the fine print and cancel. I have friends clean the place. They do a good job but they're not pro cleaners.  Still, floor will be vacuumed, dusted lightly, sheets and towels will be clean, trash taken out. If you're expecting more, get the hell out and rent a hotel.

Thank you so much for considering staying in my lovely home. I hope to hear from you soon! 

Enjoy New York City!!!!!

St. Mark's Place is the hub of the East Village, close to all transportation (for east or west side) and NYU, Cooper Union. neighborhood_overview: The Upper West Side—bracketed by Central Park and Riverside Park, and distinguished by regal, two-towered apartment buildings along Central Park West—is a place where you can frequently see families pushing strollers, walking dogs and, on weekends, settling in for brunch at mainstays like Sarabeth's.  Of course, it's not all residential. There's culture, in the form of the American Museum of Natural History, the Beacon Theatre and Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts. And plenty of shopping, eating and nightlife as well. Read on for details about what to see and do. --Entertainment-- If downtown is defined by rock 'n' roll and Midtown is all about Broadway’s glitz and glamour, the Upper West Side is where highbrow entertainment hits its highest notes. Exhibit A: Lincoln Center, a 16.3-acre complex that's home to 11 performing arts organizations—among them the New York Philharmonic, Jazz at Lincoln Center, the Metropolitan Opera and the New York City Ballet. transit: Getting around New York City can be very easy or you can make it quite adventuresome. Subway, taxis and uber all at your fingertips. Good old fashion walking is always an option too! :) Taxi.   This is probably the best method to get around New York City if you are in a group of 2-4 people, but it's not always the fastest. NYC is notorious for traffic, and you can get stuck in it in a taxi.  You can easily get anywhere in Manhattan for no more than 10 - 15, split between a group, this is not much more than a subway ride (2.75 per person), and it eliminates your chances of getting lost.  When at your hotel, ask your concierge or a doorman for a taxi and they will get one for you.  When on the street, simply look for taxis with their light on top lit but no “off duty” marked.  Walking.  New York City is the world’s greatest walking city.  All five boroughs can be explored on foot, but Manhattan is probably the easiest and most popular for pedestrians. neighborhood_overview: The East Village is by far the most vibrant neighborhood of New York City. Jam-packed with unique bars, restaurants, and shops for all budgets, you won't run out of things to do even if you never venture beyond walking distance. Our street itself is pretty quiet and residential though. We live kitty-corner to Tompkins Square Park if you need your fix of greenery.
notes: We have a small non-shedding dog named Joey (who will not be present for the duration of your stay). For weekend stays, if you arrive early on Friday, my boyfriend and Joey will likely be present to let you in and welcome you to the apartment before leaving in the afternoon.  We have a window a/c in the bedroom and a fan in the living room but the bedroom a/c is generally enough to cool the entire apartment if the door is open.  Our toilet flush makes a weird sound which can startle new users :) The water temperature can fluctuate rapidly so please be careful.  Do not touch the pipes or radiator because they are hot.  There is no elevator in the building, but our place is on the ground level so that shouldn't be an issue.
transit: We are about ten minutes walk from the nearest subways - the L train to the north at 14th Street and 1st Avenue and the F train to the south at Houston and 2nd Avenue.
interaction: We will be available by email and phone if you need help finding anything in the apartment or if you're having any trouble. Please reach out to us before contacting the super. We're also happy to give restaurant/other recommendations in the neighborhood!
house_rules: No smoking and keep the noise down at night.  Please lock the windows when you leave. The door locks on its own.  You can use the space heater if the bedroom gets cold but please turn it off when you're not using it, especially when you're not home, to save electricity.  Feel free to use any kitchen supplies - dishes, toaster, pots, etc - but please don't use metal on non-stick cookware. The trash chute is in the hallway and the recycling is in the backyard area. No need to put your sheets away, the cleaning service will take care of it.  Most importantly, please put your keys back in the lockbox when you leave.

a former NYC public school teacher, currently  a writer and avid traveler. space: You'll love our beautiful one bedroom in the heart of the Lower East Side in downtown Manhattan. The bedroom has plenty of space and light even with our super comfortable queen-sized bed, dresser and a spacious closet. The living room is well-lit and beautifully decorated if we do say so ourselves! a former NYC public school teacher, currently  a writer and avid traveler. When I'm not writing I can be found walking my adopted dog Justice to the Saint Nicholas dog park for some fun in the sun. My home in Harlem suits me because it's in an energetic, vibrant, and diverse community. My neighborhood is a wonderful place to live and I'm always meeting new people thanks to Justice. neighborhood_overview: NoMad, short for “North of Madison Square Park,” is the latest New York neighborhood to get portmanteau’ed. And like Soho and Tribeca, which were shabby commercial districts before they became artists’ enclaves, NoMad is becoming a luxury-housing magnet. Among the new condos that are gleaming like sequins in this longtime hub of the wholesale garment industry is 212 Fifth Avenue, a 48-unit condo conversion at West 26th Street from a team led by the developer Madison Equities. Like many NoMad edifices, No. 212 has a vaguely medieval style—indeed, the views from some of its apartments are of a façade adorned with sword-clasping knights. But NoMad is coming out of the Dark Ages and into the light. “This was a commercial area, and that kind of worked against it for a while,” says Efraim Tessler, an associate broker with Keller Williams New York City. “But New Yorkers are always looking for a hidden gem.” In another telltale sign, rentals are going condo, like at 88 and 90 Lexington Avenue,

At the end of my block is one of the most beautiful parks in all of Manhattan (Fort Tryon) full of Revolutionary War history and great foliage. neighborhood_overview: Northern Tribeca is calmer (not too many tourists) yet in close proximity to Soho (one block away), which has all the high-end shopping as well as the cheaper shopping strip along Broadway. There are great restaurants and lounges and cute cafes to explore.  The loft is also walking distance to the World Trade Center, 9/11 memorial, St. Paul's Chapel and all the historical charm of the Financial District which is immediately south of TriBeCa. And if you'd like to explore the more ethnic parts of New York, Little Italy and Chinatown are also nearby (less than 10 min walk).
notes: The Neighborhood I particularly love this area as TriBeCa is super famous for its food and lounge scene. There are countless top-rated and in some cases Michelin-starred restaurants in the area that are a gourmand's dream-come-true, as well as more hip and off-beat places like Macao Trading Company, Cafe Noir, and other interesting spots. There are also lots of cool art galleries as well as Hudson River Park to go walking or running. The TriBeCa Wholefoods is also close by. What I also like about this part of TriBeCa (northern part) is that it's much calmer yet in close proximity to Soho (one block away), which has all the high-end shopping as well as the cheaper shopping strip along Broadway. And if you're like me and a sucker for both, then hands down, this is the best location. There are also tons of cute restaurants in tree-lined streets to explore. The loft is also walking distance to the World Trade Center, 9/11 memorial, St. Paul's Chapel and all the historical charm of the Fina
transit: The other great thing is as Manhattan Island narrows on the way downtown, all the subways converge which makes getting around from Tribeca quick and easy. I'm two blocks from the A/C/E (which provides direct access to Penn Station, Port Authority, and Times Square) and one block from the 6, which goes directly to Grand Central Station and up the East Side to Museum Mile, and the N/Q/R. The 1 is about a 5 minute walk away. Canal Street, a major thoroughfare, provides quick transportation east or west and will take you to Chinatown if you go further East.

It's located on arguably the best street in NYC with a cafe, laundromat, top bars and restaurants and cobblestone streets just outside the door. The West Village is quaint, gorgeous, and packed with character....this home shares the same qualities. This location has very limited hotels, so it's a rare chance to wake up in the West Village.  Enjoy!

neighborhood_overview: Enjoy the West Village's eclectic cafes, top restaurants, cobblestone streets, quaint stores, high-end shopping, cupcake cafes, buzzing bars and fun night life. Steps from Citibike, the Hudson River, the Spotted Pig, Wallse, White Horse Tavern, Frankies 570, The High Line, Magnolia Bakery, Murrays Cheese Shop, and other excellent restaurants/bars/charming stores/high-end shopping.
notes: A beautiful dog usually lives in the apartment, but he will be with me during your stay! I have a fan in my room which I use at night for white noise--not necessary, but should you want it. Also, there is a Bose wireless stereo should you want to play low music.  Note:  This is a pre-war building from 1911 and is incredibly charming, but surely worn and loved in place. For example:  the pine plank floors are gorgeous and my favorite part, but aged! The heating has never been an issue for me, but you are unable to control the thermostat personally, which is typical for pre-war buildings in NYC.  Simple kitchen (half-fridge). None of this is an issue for me, I actually love the quirks and charm, but I want to be transparent so people are clear about what to expect!
transit: Many options! Very walkable area (my favorite way of getting around). Citibike  Subway: 1/2/3/9, A/C/E I always recommend Hopstop for walking, biking and mass transit directions. Their site includes maps, subway recommendations, and a foolproof guide to getting around NYC:  (website hidden)
interaction: Guests will have exclusive use of the apartment during their stay.
house_rules: Please be respectful. This is a very tight-knit community.  The fireplace does not work--do not use!  No smoking No pets No parties No loud music
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about:
Hi there,

I consider myself a confident, outgoing, and curious person. I work at a luxury travel company that allows me to explore the world--from tracking gorillas in East Africa to swimming alongside sharks in Thailand. My apartment is packed with keepsakes from around the world:  a berber door I lugged home from Morocco, marble candlesticks from Vietnam, and a silk Ikat weaving from Cambodia to name a few! 

I am a huge fan of homes with character, and this one fits the bill! I worked hard to create a space I really love in NYC and hope that the travelers who stay here enjoy it, too! My home is small, but it's got everything I need, and I love the vibe of the apartment. And you can't beat the location. I go to the coffee shop downstairs nearly every day, and walk to work along the Hudson River--just one block away. 

Hope you enjoy it!

Katie

host_about:
I am a Harlem native and a bonafide New Yorker who is still awe-inspired by both our city skyline and the red sea of traffic lights at night. I Love this city and there's no place I rather be---except maybe for on top of the world. But, staying here, near the Crossroads, comes pretty close.

I'm a homebody who balances butterflies, chases thrills and blesses my belly. Roaming endlessly is my therapy.. 

My favorite pastimes in the City are:

- stumbling into neighborhood bookstores and gift shops
- hitting up an open mic or art gallery
- park hopping in the summers after my favorite artists and musicians
- touring the City with my brother, for whom it will never get old
- visiting everything from Museum Mile to the Museum of Sex
- randomly attending First Saturdays at the B'klyn Museum every purple moon
- finding new ways to enjoy African and Caribbean foods nearly every weekend
- stuffing dumplings in my bag, with two scoops of Ginger and Lychee ice cream in a cone in the other hand
- dining on the delicious authentic Asian cuisine of China and Koreatown
- and, staring at the Brooklyn Bridge

Hi I'm  Ephraim, 

a former NYC public school teacher, currently  a writer and avid traveler. Some of the places I've been are Morocco, Italy, Colombia, Cuba, Israel, Argentina, Brazil, Puerto Rico, Dominican Republic as well as many of the American States. When I'm not writing I can be found walking my adopted dog Justice to the Saint Nicholas dog park for some fun in the sun. I grew up in Denver Colorado but have lived in New York for 28 years and counting. I am familiar with much of NYC and I can't imagine living in any other place.  My home in Harlem suits me because it's in an energetic, vibrant, and diverse community. My neighborhood is a wonderful place to live and I'm always meeting new people thanks to Justice. On some nights I like to go to the local lounge and listen to Jazz, soul, and blues music. 

I love Film and am happy to share my film collection with you. I have hundreds of my favorite movies and you can watch any of them. A few of my favorites are True Romance, A Clockwork Orange, A Nightmare on Elm Street, Cool Hand Luke, Taxi Driver, and The Princess Bride. 

I ask that you treat my home with the same respect you would expect from me in your home. That means being respectful of my neighbors and community. Putting things back in their place for the next guest to enjoy, and caring for my property as you care for your own. In other words my home is your home. Welcome to Harlem NYC!

neighborhood_overview: We know you don't need a primer on Greenwich Village, nor do you need to be told why it's among the most desirable neighborhoods in New York City. But this isn't just any part of Greenwich Village. Lower Fifth Avenue, with its high concentration of historic co-ops and townhouses, is often known as the "Gold Coast." In fact, the handful of blocks from 9th to 12th Streets, between Fifth and Sixth Avenues are considered the most coveted in all the Village. This street is a magnetic address that attracts professionals and philanthropists, actors and artists, publishers and politicos, celebrities and cave-dwellers, novelists and nabobs. One of the safest neighborhoods in the city with low-key round-the-clock activity. A relatively quiet street, unlike those south of the square or west of Sixth Avenue where there's a higher concentration of clubs, collegiates, and commercial establishments. This neighborhood has an active and effective block Association. The organization has successfully red

neighborhood_overview: The East Village (EV) is known for its cool bars and nightlife, great restaurants, and music venues. It is very hipster, artsy and unique. My block, specifically, is a living reminder of the East Village's punk-rock past. Significant moments in counterculture history happened all along the street: Abbie Hoffman invented the Yippies at No. 30 in 1967; Andy Warhol, the Velvet Underground, and Jimi Hendrix performed at now-gone experimental nightclub Electric Circus, before it closed in 1971; and gallery 51X backed eighties-era graffiti artists like Keith Haring and Basquiat. Today, the street's grasp on culture lies mostly within its diverse restaurants (frankfurters at Crif Dogs, Israeli cuisine at Hummus Place) and storefronts. And though these aren’t quite as anti-establishment as they once were—there’s nothing too rebellious about sidewalk vendors hawking plastic sunglasses—some glam stalwarts still remain, like Trash & Vaudeville and Andy's Chee-Pees, where you can still sift throug
notes: Good to know: the apartment is on the 4th floor of a walk-up building. The stairs will provide you with a bit of a work-out!
transit: There is extremely convenient public transportation. We are just 1-2 blocks from the 6, N, Q and R subway lines.  Public transportation is extremely convenient: we are just 1 block from the F and J lines. And 5 minute walk from B,D lines. So you are 20 mins away from MoMa, Central Park, Midtown, Empire State Building, Times Square and other tourist attractions.  We are walking distance to SoHo, East Village, West Village, Nolita, and Alphabet City. And have very easy access to most of Brooklyn. neighborhood_overview: I love this neighborhood and to prove my point I have lived here since the 70s. It's the REAL DEAL. Only two New York avenues to the Broadway Theater District and the Broadway theaters.  The well groomed parks and piers of the HUDSON RIVER are only 2 1/2 New York avenues away - walking distance.  There you will find the Circle Line boats which offer many trips including a full circle tour around the island of Manhattan.  Also at the pier is the Intrepid Museum, an original American Navy aircraft carrier taken out of service, with all kinds of exhibits.  There is a walking and biking pathway along the Hudson River (with no cars) going from Midtown all the way to Battery Park in Lower Manhattan as well as going uptown to Riverside Drive, the boat basin, and other attractions along the river.  There are also restaurants on some of the piers and one outdoor restaurant only a few blocks from my apartment where you can watch the sunset over the Hudson River. If you like to walk and I do the
notes: I have been extremely happy here for almost 40 years.  It's location, location, location.  And before booking please understand this is not a hotel.  It's my home where  I live.  It's an old building with high ceilings and thick walls.  It's a one flight walk-up (no elevator).  It is not a luxury building but a safe, clean, and comfortable building in a fabulous location.   I do not provide breakfast but I do provide complimentary wine.  Also I am extremely flexible about checking in and checking out times.   This means that you can maximize your stay by checking in as early as you like and checking out as late as you like if nobody else is checking in or out.  However I MUST know before booking your approximate check in and check out times so I can make my own plans around it and also to be sure to get you the keys and get them back when leaving.  If arriving and/or departing by plane I need to know itinerary (flight numbers, airlines, departure city, etc)  so I can track your flight.

neighborhood_overview: The Lower East Side of Manhattan is great - there’s restaurants, cafes, bars, shops and galleries within blocks of the apartment. East Village is only a few steps away, along with Soho, Nolita, Little Italy, and Chinatown all being within walking distance.  There’s some great grocery markets right in the area as well, including Whole Foods, Union Market, and Essex Street Market (indoor farmers market).  If you want to spend some time in the park, you’ll be right near Tomkins Square Park, which also has a fantastic dog run for those traveling with pets. A lot of New York’s attractions are also really easy to get to, such as Empire State Building, Statue of Liberty, Time Square, and Central Park. Subways and buses are only a couple blocks away.
notes: Checkin is at 3PM or later, and checkout is 11AM. I'm happy to be flexible and accommodate, on a situational basis, as long as the apartment isn't otherwise booked. Please note, this apartment is dog friendly ... it will be perfectly clean for your arrival, however, those with dog allergies might be better off with another option.

neighborhood_overview: The Lower East Side, sometimes abbreviated as LES, is a neighborhood in the southeastern part of the New York City borough of Manhattan, roughly located between the Bowery and the East River, and Canal Street and Houston Street. Traditionally an immigrant, working-class neighborhood, it began rapid gentrification in the mid-2000s, prompting The National Trust for Historic Preservation to place the neighborhood on their list of America's Most Endangered Places.  It's still one of the true NYC neighborhood experiences you'll ever have. See it now before it changes!!!!

neighborhood_overview: I have lived all over the city, but once I found myself in the East Village, nothing else compared. It's a little busier now than it used to be, but that's a good thing. The restaurants can't be beat, everything from raw to local to gourmet Mexican, amazing Italian, Indian... the list goes on. A mere two blocks from Tompkins Square Park, the street itself also has 2 gardens on it, so it's out of the concrete jungle fray.  Wandering around the neighborhood you'll find a lot of independent designers with small shops, the famous St Mark's Place is 4 blocks away, Union Square 5 blocks away, antiques, and an array of characters to keep your people watching pleasures at an all time high.
transit: The apartment is conveniently located 3 blocks from the L train, which will get you anywhere in the city.  Taxis are usually flowing--although worth noting that it's much harder between 8:30 and 9:30, and noon-2.  When you need a car, LES car service is a favorite: (PHONE NUMBER HIDDEN).
access: Guests have full access to the apartment, including  a closet. The only thing off limits is the rooftop as the building does not have a permit for that so it's a liability.  But that's even better for you as you don't have anyone treading above you!
house_rules: This is a quiet place, so it's not for those who want to throw parties while visiting the city.   It is a no-shoe apartment, for two reasons: 1. it's kind to your neighbors underneath and beside you, and 2. it's really hard to keep track of the dog poop in the street. I've wasted many hours scrubbing things off my rugs from guests new to the city streets (don't worry, the rugs in there now are all new!).   Please no smoking in the apartment.  Most important: make yourself at home and enjoy the city!
host_location: New York, New York, United States
host_about: After many many years in the Big Apple, we are dear old friends who have both decided to split our time between the mountains & country-living of upstate NY and New York City--hence we now co-host our awesome airbnb guests!  One of us is a business consultant, the other a lawyer--who are frequent travelers and lovers of great adventures outside our workdays, feeling out beautiful new places in the world, humbled along the way by how much there is to see and learn...

neighborhood_overview: Midtown Manhattan is the largest central business district in the United States[1] and ranks among the most intensely used pieces of real estate in the world. While Lower Manhattan is the main financial center, Midtown is the country's largest commercial, entertainment, and media center; Midtown Manhattan is also a growing financial center, second in importance in the United States only to Lower Manhattan's Financial District. The majority of New York City's skyscrapers, including its tallest hotels and apartment towers, lie within Midtown. The area hosts commuters and residents working in its offices, hotels, and retail establishments; many tourists, visiting residents, and students populate the district. Some areas, such as Times Square and the Fifth Avenue corridor, have large clusters of retail stores, and Times Square is the center of Broadway theatre. The Avenue of the Americas holds the headquarters of three of the four major U.S. television networks.
notes: This Neighborhood is extremely Fun and Close it all!

Take a stroll along old Riverside Drive and notice the lovely Parisian-style lights and walkways.  Equally amazing is the three blocks to magnificent Central Park.  It's also a 10-minute walk to Columbia Univ. and a couple subway stops to Lincoln Center.  It's incredibly convenient to the 96th St. express subway station which gets you to Times Square in just 2 stops and downtown in 15 minutes.   You can reach the Natural History Museum in about a 15-minute walk and a quick subway ride to the shops at Time Warner Center/Columbus Circle.   And let's not forget the fabulous and famous markets that the Upper West Side boasts;  Fairway Market and Zabars, Barzinis and Westside Market, not to mention Trader Joes and Whole Foods - all accessible by walking or a quick subway trip.

Hudson Heights is a mini-community with borders that extend from 181st Street to 193rd and from Broadway over to the Hudson River. To the immediate north of Hudson Heights sits the expansive Fort Tryon Park which, in addition to its gardens, broad playing fields, dog runs and pathways, is home of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's Cloisters Museum, with one of the finest medieval art and culture collections in the world. Hudson Heights residents are also fond of Bennett Park, with its playground and grassy patches and an unobtrusive plaque on the spot that the Park Department says marks the highest natural point of land in all of Manhattan. neighborhood_overview: Restaurants: Lots of great Cuban restaurants in the area, with Cubano Amor being my favorite (3 min walk).  It has live music most nights of the week and the food is good.  East Harlem Bottling Co has great food and a good drink selection (2 min walk).  5 minutes away from McDonalds, Wendy's, Domino's and Burger King.  Lemon Sushi does great/cheap delivery. Supermarkets: There are two super markets on 110 street (2 min walk) and one on 104 street (4 min walk).  There is a Duane Reade 3 min walk away.  There is the East River Mall on 117 street (20 min walk or 10 Uber) with Target, Aldi, Costco, Best Buy, Petco, Marshall's and Old Navy.  There is an open air plant store on 116 street (10 min walk).
notes: The subway on the weekend and holidays is slower, so make sure to plan for a longer travel time on those days.  Also, the subway at 110 St is not wheel chair accessible.  Consider taking an accessible taxi from 125 St which is a wheel chair accessible subway stop.
transit: Driving: There is a parking lot across the street from me and free parking depending on the street signs.   Most guests find parking in under 20 minutes and I have not had a guest yet who has had to pay for parking there.  There are also 2 parking lots with paid parking about a 1 min walk away (30/day). Taxi:  An Uber to Grand Central is usually around 15-20 depending on traffic. Subway: We are 2 blocks (2 min walk) away from the 110 st station on the 6 train.  We are 15 blocks (15 min walk) away from the 96 st Station on the Q train.  There are numerous buses on Lexington and 3rd Avenue. Train: Amtrak and MTA trains make stops at 125 st station - about a 10 Uber or a 15 min walk away.
access: Backyard, bedroom, 2 bathrooms, living room and kitchen.
interaction: I will be available whenever.  I usually end up socializing with my guests but I respect everyone's privacy.

host_about:
Im originally from NYC but have lived in Los Angeles for 3 years. I moved to LA to attend law school, and chose to live in Venice because of its vibrant art  culture, and laid back atmosphere which is a nice break from the hustle and bustle of LA - people seem to be friendlier and happier here, probably because they live in a beach town that is 75 degrees and sunny virtually 365 days a year.

I specifically chose my apt so I could be a 1 minute walk from the beach (and the always-entertaining boardwalk) which allows me to literally walk out my door in the morning and be surfing in the pacific in literally less than 3  minutes (The NYer in me likes things to be fast). Along with the beachside location, another major reason that I chose my apt is the fact that it has a very large private back patio that is enclosed with tall bamboo; I enjoy gardening and have transformed the patio into a lush tropical garden, planting several types of Palm trees, Aloe and Blooming Aloe, Lavender, Jasmine, Tropical Ferns, countless succulents, cacti, flowers, in addition to a variety of vegetables like arugula, lettuce, squash, different types of peppers, and herbs like rosemary and basil.

I am currently in my last year of law school, and although my school is downtown, I have found it easy to avoid the traffic with a little planning and using the GPS App Waze.

I love traveling and backpacking, and in the past couple years I've traveled to Paris, London, Amsterdam, Argentina, Berlin, India, Thailand, Laos, Indonesia, Bermuda, Honduras, Haiti, Mexico, Argentina and Malaysia.

I'd love to explore Myanmar, Africa, Russia, Vietnam, Cambodia, Spain

Some of my other favorite activities are surfing, gardening, cooking, and going to see live music. I also enjoy making art, including painting, mixed media, electroforming metals, and really any type of creative expression.  

Last but not least - I love dogs, and there is a great dog park right across the street from my apt.

host_about:
I am filmmaker (writer/director/ produce) living and working in New York City since 2008. 
I can't live without exercise .
I can't live without a bathtub. 
I can't live without books, and films - my apartment is full with them
I can't live without a great mattress and sheets.
I can't live without delivery from my fav restaurants (NYC has spoiled me)

I love travel within South East Asia. Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, Bali… The place I most want to visit is India.

As a filmmaker my passion for film is something I hope to share with my guests. 

I have a collection of over 500 DVDs in my home for your viewing pleasure, stored and alphabetized in the long white console cabinet the runs the length of the hall. There is a printed list with the names of every DVD in collection. Organized into 3 separate leather bound binders I also have a collection of documentaries, a collection of music performance DVDs, and a collection of TV shows ranging from 21 Jump Street to Ab Fab to the Sopranos.

Tell me about yourself and I'll leave a few recommendations of films for you!

If you noticed from the photos: books are also a passion for me, if not a bit of an addiction. I have an extensive collection of several hundred art books ranging in subject from painting, photography, jewelry, fashion, music, film, architecture, interior design. Everything is organized by subject. Aside from art books, I have hundreds of books related to my other interests organized by topic: biographies, books on film, books on philosophy, books on psychology, books on anthropology with a focus on shamanism, books on sociology, a section of fiction books ranging from Faulkner to Dostoevsky, and of course a collection of auction catalogues primarily contemporary art, magnificent jewelry, and special sales i.e. the property of Doris Duke, the property of Jackie Kennedy.

The books are ALOT OF FUN! Enjoy them but please put them back where you got them off the shelves, and also be delicate with the art books as they are expensive.

My style of traveling is often last minute, and for extended periods 3 weeks or more. I do a lot of my screenwriting while I travel. Sometimes I just get so over the city that I need a break, so I take off. 

My hosting style is to be as accommodating and available as possible. I treat you as if you were a friend coming to stay. I just ask the same of guests as I ask of my friends: please be respectful of my belongings and of my privacy. Throughout the home there is expensive furniture, rugs, art, books, even the wine glasses. 

It's not a museum, I live with these things in my normal life and they are meant for use. I trust my guests not to damage anything intentionally.   
Hey accidents happen though - if you stain a towel, tell me. If you do break a crystal wine glass from Riedel, and when you break it red wine spills on the 10,000 Tibetan rug please let me know. Certain things in the apartment like the rugs have to be cleaned in a special way and I wouldn't want you to make it worse. It's not going to be a big deal, accidents happen and we can work through it, just be honest. Rugs can be cleaned and wine glasses can be replaced. Just please let me know ahead of time and I won't be surprised and upset.

If I am traveling while you are staying in my place, I will have a local manager for the property to show you around when you arrive, and be on call to help if there is a problem. I love my home, and I want you to love it and be as comfortable there as I am.

Also since my super is useless I don't use him… Instead I found an ace local handyman named Ray, he's a great guy whose number I will leave. God forbid there is an issue, you can call him and he can sort it out.

neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is reminiscent of old-school Europe. In the early 1800s the area was a major port, and the building use to be a warehouse for the storage of spices. All around there are cafes, pubs, and restaurants that line cobble stone streets, and the nearby park offers a refuge from the concrete jungle life. While there is a lot going on, the apartment is quiet, which is unusual for NYC. Steps away from the East River this apartment offers a prime location for getting to and from the 4th of July Macy's Firework display, easy access to the trains for Thanksgiving Day Parade, and blocks from the Statue of Liberty.
transit: Most major subways (1, 2, 3, N, R, 4, 5, J, & M) are 3 blocks away. It takes 15 mins to get anywhere in Manhattan.  Central Park (where I work) takes 20 mins on a workday.  The A, C, E trains are 6 blocks away at Fulton Street. We are very close to the west side highway bike path as well and CitiBike is located just around the corner. Cabs are always available right outside the door.

PLEASE let me know if there is anything missing or have any problems! This is very important. We have a zero tolerance disturbance policy. This means if we hear anything, we will come and ask that you check out immediately. This is strict. That is unless you want some advice on our favorite local haunts or to grab a drink with your awesome vacation landlords. In that case, we're always here to respond to any qu
neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is not only home to me, but all of my favorite places. There are countless boutique shops, top-rated restaurants opening every time you blink (a couple that are Michelin rated), night life and performance venues, as well as art galleries and museums (the new museum is a must) all within a couple blocks. After you've explored the area and the sun is beginning to set, hop on a citi bike, or just walk the Williamsburg bridge, where a whole new world of fun awaits.  Within a five-ten minute walk lies Soho (fashion capital), the East Village (historic landmark full of bars and restaurants), and the West Village (Washington Square Park and NYU).
notes: If you stand at our front door and pick up a rock I guarantee you hit an amazing restaurant, a bar with a unique and cool vibe, or a very unlucky person. We have no fewer than 4 favorite coffee shops and none of them are Starbucks. Every time we try to save money and pledge to make our own food we shatter our resolutions within 48 hours because of how great the restaurants in NYC are (for real tho, we are not kidding). If shopping is your thing- you won't be disappointed. From new shiny things at Marc Jacobs to vintage shiny things at Vintage Underground there are shops for everyone!
access: The kitchen has everything you need to make some stellar meals (and coffee) as well as a table with seating for four. There are two gorgeously lit bedrooms, each with fresh linens and comfy beds (and their own closets full of hangers). One QUEEN bed and one FULL bed. If you have more people than we have beds, we have a futon in the living space (sleeps 1).
interaction: We wont be around to cramp your vacation style... That is unless you want some advice on our favorite local haunts or to grab a drink with your awesome vacation landlords. In that case, we're always here to respond to any questions!
house_rules: •No filming or parties. Or filming of parties, you dirty dogs! Guests are welcome but no loud music, just basic neighbor respect.  •Check-out time is 11am, no later. •Check-in time is 3PM, no earlier. Strict about these times. If you must arrive later than three, that's always fine, but check out time is strictly 11, no exceptions. If you have a late flight, there is a nearby luggage storage company you can use, or just book an extra day at the end of your trip.  Since we aren't a Frat House we ask that you treat our space like you would your Mother in Laws. (Pick up after yourselves, put things back where you found them.. etc) Also no smoking- please and thank you.

There are also several grocery stores and bodegas in the neighborhood, and tasty Latin American restaurants that I highly recommend.  My favorite thing about this location is that I have two really great parks within a 5-10 minute walk of our place; Inwood Hill Park and Fort Tryon Park, which is also the location of The Cloisters.
notes: Mi cuarto cuenta con un colchon de estilo japones, el cual es muy cómodo, sin resortes y muy bueno para la espalda. He recivido comentarios positivos de muchos huespedes.

neighborhood_overview: If you are looking for the Manhattan Experience, but find the city a little too noisy and bustling, this is your neighborhood!  Even though you are in Manhattan, this neighborhood is quiet, safe, and family friendly.   Overlooking the Hudson River, you will find some really beautiful views of the George Washington Bridge, and the Palisades.   You are located near two supermarkets, a Chase Bank, a pharmacy, and multiple restaurants right outside your door.  There is also a very excellent wine shop right up the street called Vines on Pine.  A short walk south to 181st Street will take you to a Starbucks, and a wonderful Italian restaurant called Saggio.   Heading north, you will find Fort Tryon Park, and the Cloisters Museum, a must-see collection of medieval art.
notes: We are on a fifth floor walkup.

We are also walking distance from the George Washington Bridge and the GWB bus terminal.

space: Please Read Before Booking: If you enjoy European style buildings with character, you'll love this place. The building has seen better days since it was built in 1882, but that only adds charm to it. The apartment is old and located inside of a historic building, so if you are looking for a Hilton hotel stay experience, this is probably not the right place for you. Another thing to note is that during winter months running water is more warm than hot. It's connected to the main building heating system and we can't adjust the temperature unfortunately. neighborhood_overview: The Financial District is the PERFECT location for those wanting to visit NYC!  I specifically live down here because of the wide, less-trafficky streets so me and my dog can have long, quiet walks without having to feel claustrophobic.  There are always children outside playing out in the cobble streets directly out in front of the apartment building door, and always meeting other dogs and their dog people is truly a unique FiDi thing. Next, is its proximity to the waterfront, both East and West.  Both waterfronts have been newly renovated and you can get to either within a 10 minute walk.  Imagine going on a sun-drenched walk each morning while you're in this amazing city! Finally, the Financial District is the ULTIMATE location in Manhattan for getting around.  You can pick up almost ANY MAJOR SUBWAY LINE down here, and cabs (both yellow and luxury) run here by the truckload.  And if the weather is nice, you can pick up a CitiBike right down the street and go for a nice bike ride.
notes: - Corner Unit for extra privacy - Top-of-the-line TempurPedic bed - 150 mbps superspeed wireless Internet - XL marbled bathroom - Washer & Dryer in apartment
transit: - J/Z train: literally right outside the front door.  Head over to Williamsburg in just 10-15 minutes! (Broad Street) - 4/5 train: 3 minute walk (Wall Street) - 2/3 train: 3 minute walk (Wall Street) - R train: 3 minute walk (Rector Street) - 6 train: 5 minute walk (Bowling Green) - A/C train: 10 minute walk (Fulton Street) - Citibike stations:  3 within walking distance, with the closest being 2 blocks away - Ferry:  It is a 10 minute walk to the Wall Street Ferry Pier, which takes you to destinations such as Jersey City and Red Hook (where IKEA is)
access: - Penthouse rooftop equipped with sun beds, couches, outdoor shower, and BBQ grill (spring & summer months only) - Fully equipped gym with yoga studio - Lounge with billiards, golf simulator, ping pong, and full kitchen - Concierge - 24 Hour Doorman - Spa directly across the street - Bobby Van's Steakhouse in the building

neighborhood_overview: The beautiful, geographically elevated "Hudson Heights" section of Washington Heights stretches West and North from about 181st Street and Fort Washington Avenue, which is the SouthEast corner of this sub-neighborhood. It is bordered to the West by the Hudson River, and to the North by Fort Tryon Park. Hudson Heights is a tree-filled, pet-filled oasis with restaurants and grocery stores conveniently available on 181st Street and 187th Street. Bennet Park (which has a playground and many folks walking dogs) is just outside the building. The larger Fort Tryon Park (with its incredible flower garden, views of the Hudson, enormous dog run, beautiful New Leaf Cafe, and the Cloisters Museum) is about 7 blocks north, and Fort Washington Park, which extends along the Hudson River and is fantastic for running or walking, is accessible from 181st Street, just a couple blocks to the south.
notes: Fortunately, this building is a quiet, peaceful, pet- and family-friendly living space. It is surrounded by well-tended gardens both outside the front of the building and inside the courtyard. Neighbors are friendly, and amenities are well maintained.
transit: The A Express train and the 1 train both service the neighborhood for easy access to the rest of the city (it's about a 20 minute ride to midtown). For those with cars, there are two nearby and reasonably priced parking garages on Cabrini Avenue: One is part of a housing complex called Castle Village and the other is further north just before 190th Street.
access: Guests have full and private access to the entire apartment. They also have access to the new washers and dryers in the laundry room located in the basement of the apartment building.
interaction: I will be available to guests via text, phone, email, or AirBnB messaging as needed.
house_rules: - This apartment is located in a friendly, quiet building. To maintain this rare and cherished atmosphere, noise, especially late at night, should be kept to a minimum.

neighborhood_overview: Quiet streets with old world charm, yet every convenience just steps away, the Gold Coast offers gracious and genteel living unequaled in Manhattan. One block from the West Village, a couple more from Greenwich Village…the city's most talked-about restaurants are literally steps from your door, while New York's poshest, style-making shops are found a few minutes' walk over in Bleecker Street or Soho. We know you don't need a primer on Greenwich Village, nor do you need to be told why it's among the most desirable neighborhoods in New York City. But this isn't just any part of Greenwich Village. Lower Fifth Avenue, with its high concentration of historic co-ops and townhouses, is often known as the "Gold Coast." In fact, the handful of blocks from 9th to 12th Streets, between Fifth and Sixth Avenues are considered the most coveted in all the Village. name: Chic Greenwich Village One Bedroom
summary: Living on MacDougal street seemingly resurrects the souls that once called Greenwich Village their stomping grounds. Creativity becomes you as it did J.D. Salinger when he created Holden Caulfield at Cafe Reggio. Historic grounds breed inspiration.
space: This apartment will undoubtedly provide a far more relaxing experience than many other city spaces. It is located in the back of the building which begets utter silence and substantially more sunshine. This pre-war building has not only character but a renovated inside with granite countertops, updated appliances, a stainless steel stove, sanded and polished hardwood floors and soaring ceilings. The space accommodates two, but you are welcome to invite guests free of charge. One of the most gratifying amenities of this building is the rooftop. It hovers above the buildings around it and has a sweeping 360 degree view of the city. It's perfect for meditating, landscape painting or just hanging out with friends. The fire escape leading from the bedroom is also a safe and relaxing place to enjoy some fresh air (and smells from the restaurants below!) Living here is truly a dream, and if I didn't have to leave, I wouldn't! I hope you enjoy your stay and please don't hesitate to contact me

neighborhood_overview: The possibility for adventure is endless within and beyond the infamous MacDougal Street, which is lined with historic architecture and cobble stone streets. With worldly cuisine, live music lounges, comedy clubs, bars and nightlife activities, independent theaters, parks and dog runs, easy transportation and the hudson river, you are truly left without a dull moment. Bodegas surround you but Morton Williams is your best bet for quick groceries. There's a laundry mat on Thompson street and city bikes on Carmine. One block up is the West 4th station where the A, C, E, B, D, F, and M lines will transport you to virtually every inch of New York City. Being in Greenwich, you've got the West Village, Union Square, Soho and the East Village on each side of you. MacDougal Street makes for a balanced lifestyle because it's peaceful in the mornings and lively at night. I like to think of NYC as the epicenter of the USA, and Greenwich as the epicenter of NYC. neighborhood_overview: Very close to subways, supermarkets, delis and local shops all within blocks. Lots of restaurants and galleries near by (please check out our guidebook-a few stops on the subway will take you to the hot spots). Please have a slice of authentic New York pizza during your stay from the pizzeria on Broadway, it's great and cheap! An adorable new bar on Evergreen and Moffat and a new coffee shop with sweets and breakfast on Wilson and Moffat- it's called Routine.
notes: Great up and coming neighborhood, the block is full of young professionals, students and artists.  This is in a great location to explore many parts of Brooklyn and access Manhattan.  The Lower East Side of Manhattan is about a 20 minute ride (Essex Street stop) on the train a block from the house (J/Z line).  The L train is a 5 block walk - it takes you through parts of Bushwick (Morgan/Jefferson stops) and into the heart of Williamsburg (Bedford) in 15 minutes - or to 1st Avenue/Union Square in 25 minutes.  There are many connections to get anywhere.
transit: We are a half block walk from the Chauncey (J/Z) station, and a 5 minute walk from either the Wilson (L) station, or the Bushwick/Aberdeen (L) station. Both trains offer fast access to the city in 25-30 minutes and make excellent connections with other train lines.  You can get to the Lower East Side in about 20 minutes or Union Square in 25 minutes. Quick cab ride from LGA and JFK, about 30 minutes depending on time of day. Or grab the AirTran to the J train by public transportation, it leaves you a half a block from the apartment.  Uber is a great application you can download should you prefer a cab.
access: There is wifi in the apartment and cable TV.  Extra towels and necessities are located in the TV storage cabinet.
interaction: Guests are free to come and go as you will be provided with keys upon arrival and any guidance as were are local and available. Please arrive at your convenience after 3pm as the keys are in a lockbox and you will be provided with the combination code.
house_rules: No smoking inside or pets allowed.  We just ask that guests are respectful of others and the apartment.  Two guests per stay, unless discussed otherwise.  This is a quiet building please leave the party outside AND ENJOY!

Boasting the best of, well, everything, Chelsea is an inexhaustible grid of beyond-hip bars, bookshops, cafes, clubs, and galleries that cater to even the most exacting tastes. Minutes from the High Line and the Hudson River, a 10 min walk to SoHo and a 7 minute walk to the West Village. The apartment has a huge sun drenched living room,  New York style with exposed brick wall. There is a clean bathroom and fully equipped kitchen.  Bed room facing the court yard so peace and quiet at night even in the middle of bustling Manhattan! Guests have access to all amenities and I will meet and greet you upon arrival! I will also assist with anything you might want to know about the Big Apple and help make sure your stay exceeds your expectations!
